title: For Sale:  S&W 325 Thunder Ranch 45 ACP
location: Cary, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent: For sale is a lightly used Smith and Wesson 325 Thunder Ranch in 45 ACP.  It is in like-new condition with about 350 rounds through it.  Includes original Thunder Ranch case, 15 moon clips and a demooning tool.Price is $950 for a local sale, which is greatly preferred.$1005 for remote sale (extra covers shipping and outgoing FFL fee), and we'll have to come up with an escrow of some sort or have the actual sale go through the FFLs.Other offers may be considered, but I'm in no rush to sell, so don't bother with a low-ball offer.== Condition ==There are some signs of wear proportional to the amount of use the gun has had.  Cylinder ring is just barely starting.  I have a small piece of electrical tape on the frame behind the trigger to prevent the trigger stop adjustment from marring the finish (although factory testing already put a little bit of a dot on it).  Mechanically the gun is in effectively new condition.  I haven't noticed any changes from a break-in period (probably due to the factory tuning).== Performance ==The gun is light for its size, which is the reason it's not working out for me.  I wanted something for high volume shooting, but I'm a bit recoil sensitive so this isn't the best choice due to its weight.  Fit and finish are excellent.  Trigger is amazing.  Revolvers tend to have good single-action pulls anyway, but this one is in a class of its own.  At the current setting, overtravel is so small that I can hardly see the trigger move when the hammer drops.  Double action pull is very smooth, but on the heavy side since it's a defensive pistol.I largely bought the gun for quick reloads using moon clips.  I could not be more happy with that aspect of it.  The chamfered chambers are fantastic and make 45 ACP moon clips behave almost like a magnet.  I had fun practicing with full-weight dummy rounds.  I could basically "toss" the loaded moon clip at the open cylinder from six inches away and have an 80% chance of it aligning itself and dropping in.  I realize that sounds like a sales pitch, but this honestly is the main thing I'm going to miss about the gun if it sells, so I figured I'd talk about it a little.== Moon Clips ==Moon clips actually aren't necessary.  I fired many cylinders with loose rounds.  The extractor star doesn't catch, of course, but the cases mostly fall out if you point the gun up, and the ones that don't just require a finger flick to pull out.  This is convenient when at the range just shooting for fun.The 15 moon clips that are included have performed well with no problems.  I recommend pliers wrapped in electrical tape (just to reduce scratching your brass and clips) for mooning, and the included demooning tool is quite easy to use.Thanks for looking.
